external_knowledge:
- Full powerlifting events (SBD) involve three lifts: squat, bench press, and deadlift;
- The average total weight lifted is calculated by summing the weights lifted in all three lifts and dividing by the number of athletes;
- Coaches are ranked based on the average performance of their athletes in these events.

- "Titans" refers to the strongest athletes;
- "Collectively lifted" means the sum of the best squat, bench press, and deadlift weights;
- "Division" refers to the category or class of the athlete, such as mp, open, or nov.

- "shining stars" refers to athletes who are ranked in the top 3 within their weight classes;
- "lifted the heaviest weights" refers to the total weight lifted in all three lifts;
- "still under the guidance of their coaches" means the athletes have an active association with their coaches (i.e., `end_date` is NULL).

- "Strongest athletes" refers to those with the highest total weight lifted in a competition;
- "Coaching history" includes the longest association with a coach and the duration of that association;
- "Training performance" is represented by the average weight lifted during training sessions;
- "Peak performance" is the best total weight lifted in any competition, and the equipment used during that performance is also of interest.

- "Titans of each weight class" refers to the athletes in different weight categories;
- "First grand event" refers to the competition with `competition_id = 1`;
- "Lifted more than a mere trifle" means the average total weight lifted is greater than 0.

- The "first training session" refers to the earliest training session recorded for each athlete.;
- The "best competition performance" refers to the highest total weight lifted in any competition for each athlete.;
- The improvement percentage is calculated using the formula: \(\left( \frac{\text{best_total_weight_competition} - \text{total_weight_first_session}}{\text{total_weight_first_session}} \right) \times 100\).;

- 'SBD' stands for Squat, Bench, and Deadlift, a common combination in weightlifting competitions;
- The average total weight lifted is calculated by summing the weights lifted across all three lifts and dividing by the number of athletes in the division;
- Divisions are categories used to group athletes based on criteria such as age, weight, and experience.

- 'open' division includes weight classes between 48-59 kg, 60-75 kg, 76-90 kg, and 91-120 kg;
- Weight classes outside these ranges are categorized as 'unknown';
- The query only includes divisions with at least one athlete.
